Pinus sabiniana is commonly known as the gray pine or foothill pine tree. 
It is native to California, specifically to the foothills of the Sierra Nevada and the Coast Ranges. 
It has a distinct grayish-brown bark that grows in plates, giving the tree a rough texture. 
The needles of the Pinus sabiniana are long, slender and form bundles of three, and can range in color from green to blue-green. 
The cones produced by the tree are large and heavy with sharp spines, and are commonly used for decorative purposes. 
The Gray Pine is a drought-tolerant species with an extensive root system and can grow up to 120 feet tall. 
It is commonly found in foothill regions and open woodlands.
